Signed-off-by: Benjamin Böhmke <benjamin@boehmke.net>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jamlee-t/moby/commits/66459cc6236e86ce926ccab8be9998cff090657e"},{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jamlee-t/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jamlee-t/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jamlee-t/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Signed-off-by: J-jaeyoung <jjy600901@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jamlee-t/moby/commits/19eda6b9a2991733a7e5b8fb0c435bf55846461f"},{"sha":"27801b9ef807ce64b55b4c4ccd9a02248ae6bce2","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"vendor: update github.com/Microsoft/hcsshim v0.8.10 (back to tagged release)

This switches the hcsshim dependency back to tagged releases, instead of the special
"moby" branch. This makes the dependency align with both BuildKit and containerd,
which use these versions.

The switch to the "moby" branch was done in 286547848751229fa14974da389e1d4c676d8ee5,
to bring in a fix for image import, without having to bring in additional changes;

> We changed to the moby branch for a couple of reasons:
>
> - Allows us to take this important change without needing to also pull in all
>   of the other work that has been going on in the repo.
> - moby uses an older set of APIs exposed from hcsshim, based on the HCS v1
>   functionality. Going forwards, we have discussed deprecating/removing these
>   APIs from the mainline branch in hcsshim, so our thinking was we could keep
>   this moby branch around to ensure we don't break compatibility there.
>
> (...) Long term, the best path here is to get moby using containerd as the
> backend on Windows, which should alleviate these issues.

full diff: https://github.com/Microsoft/hcsshim/compare/9dcb42f100215f8d375b4a9265e5bba009217a85..v0.8.10

Change-Id: Ie660dfbab51ff094c6ec8ca45646584b503b322d","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mansnils/tensorflow/commits/5211597d912dbef1242d7bf38b8bdf2b365e9872"},{"sha":"6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Move `SummaryWriter.{set_,}as_default()` impls up to the base class

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

Change-Id: Ifa6d88ba2e87f1eaae96fa3ea2fe3f6c5b73234a","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mansnils/tensorflow/commits/6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3"},{"sha":"6a049381fb0989ea8f989dc9cea7e1fd588290a8","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"[retry]Use self.handle inside ResourceVariable to allow tf.distribute to customize
handle behavior

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

Manually confirmed by restoring the resize_bilinear kernel and checking
that the Xtensa build command from #48516 passes.

The latency change for the keyword benchmark is as follows:

Fusion F1:
```
 make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade run_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

before:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner took 177927 ticks (177 ms).

KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 34251 ticks (34 ms)
```

after:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner took 178575 ticks (178 ms).

KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 34333 ticks (34 ms)
```

Hifimini:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=hifimini XTENSA_CORE=mini1m1m_RG run_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

before:
```

KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 90231 ticks (90 ms)
```

after:

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

This should allow us to remove the logic in the event system that
tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yohanceli/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yohanceli/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to

fake_quant_utils.

By this change, the QDQ can be inserted immediately after the tf.FakeQuant* ops
being unwrapped. This makes the QDQ inserting more flexible because all the
min/max operands of the tf.FakeQuant* ops have been folded already.

This patch also moves the related rewrites from the prepare_tf file to the
fake_quant_utils.

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

This should allow us to remove the logic in the event system that
tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

Change-Id: Icecbb71f1c385b2cc7fbc9dee01862fb4882eb24","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/9df99991066cb80caedf4579c04ee0a213b7bde6"},{"sha":"80d8d2525f148541c83a0a989a0663a24d747262","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Include both the global and thread-local extra jit context in the JIT signature.

Previously if there was a thread-local context set we would include it in preference to the global context. However since the "extra context" is an opaque object with no particular semantics as far as the C++ code is concerned, it makes more sense to include both local and global as part of the cache key. Just because the thread-local values are equal it doesn't mean that they completely override the global values.

Change-Id: Icecbb71f1c385b2cc7fbc9dee01862fb4882eb24","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/9df99991066cb80caedf4579c04ee0a213b7bde6"},{"sha":"80d8d2525f148541c83a0a989a0663a24d747262","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Include both the global and thread-local extra jit context in the JIT signature.

Previously if there was a thread-local context set we would include it in preference to the global context. However since the "extra context" is an opaque object with no particular semantics as far as the C++ code is concerned, it makes more sense to include both local and global as part of the cache key. Just because the thread-local values are equal it doesn't mean that they completely override the global values.

Change-Id: Icecbb71f1c385b2cc7fbc9dee01862fb4882eb24","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/9df99991066cb80caedf4579c04ee0a213b7bde6"},{"sha":"80d8d2525f148541c83a0a989a0663a24d747262","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Include both the global and thread-local extra jit context in the JIT signature.

Previously if there was a thread-local context set we would include it in preference to the global context. However since the "extra context" is an opaque object with no particular semantics as far as the C++ code is concerned, it makes more sense to include both local and global as part of the cache key. Just because the thread-local values are equal it doesn't mean that they completely override the global values.

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/szutenberg/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if

[{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. [{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

tracks nested event dispatches.

a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

This should allow us to remove the logic in the event system that
tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

If provisioner configuration or connection info includes sensitive
values, we need to unmark them before calling the provisioner. Failing
to do so causes serialization to error.

Unlike resources, we do not need to capture marked paths here, so we
just discard the marks.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/9c580335e303610f96e01cfa8859ea6ee78ea87e"},{"sha":"4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"terraform: Hide maybe-sensitive provisioner output

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"}]

This shows consistent improvement over openCV benchmarks, and we measure
even larger improvements on our internal workloads.

For example, for 320x480, `32FC*`, we can see a ~5% improvement}, as
`320=2^6*5` and `480=2^5*3*5`, so the improved radix3 version is used.

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

This should allow us to remove the logic in the event system that
tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

[{"sha":"d686f3f16a796025ce32cfb431b70eef6de1934e","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Add `.old` prefix to reconciler modules","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/devsumanmdn/react/commits/d686f3f16a796025ce32cfb431b70eef6de1934e"},{"sha":"376d5c1b5aa17724c5fea9412f8fcde14a7b23f1","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Split cross-package types from implementation

Some of our internal reconciler types have leaked into other packages.
Usually, these types are treated as opaque; we don't read and write
to its fields. This is good.

However, the type is often passed back to a reconciler method. For
example, React DOM creates a FiberRoot with `createContainer`, then
passes that root to `updateContainer`. It doesn't do anything with the
root except pass it through, but because `updateContainer` expects a
full FiberRoot, React DOM is still coupled to all its fields.

I don't know if there's an idiomatic way to handle this in Flow. Opaque
types are simlar, but those only work within a single file. AFAIK,
there's no way to use a package as the boundary for opaqueness.

The immediate problem this presents is that the reconciler refactor will
involve changes to our internal data structures. I don't want to have to
fork every single package that happens to pass through a Fiber or
FiberRoot, or access any one of its fields. So my current plan is to
share the same Flow type across both forks. The shared type will be a
superset of each implementation's type, e.g. Fiber will have both an
`expirationTime` field and a `lanes` field. The implementations will
diverge, but not the types.

To do this, I lifted the type definitions into a separate module.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/devsumanmdn/react/commits/376d5c1b5aa17724c5fea9412f8fcde14a7b23f1"},{"sha":"17f582e0453b808860be59ed3437c6a426ae52de","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Add forked copies of reconciler modules

Then transform the internal imports:

Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Script for syncing changes between forks (#18550)

Adds command `yarn merge-fork`.

```sh
yarn merge-fork --base-dir=packages/react-reconciler/src ReactFiberWorkLoop
```

This will take all the changes in `ReactFiberWorkLoop.new.js` and apply
them to `ReactFiberWorkLoop.old.js`.

You can merge multiple modules at a time:

```sh
yarn merge-fork \
  --base-dir=packages/react-reconciler/src \
  ReactFiberWorkLoop \
  ReactFiberBeginWork \
  ReactFiberCompleteWork \
  ReactFiberCommitWork
```

You can provide explicit "old" and "new" file names. This only works
for one module at a time:

```sh
yarn merge-fork \
  --base-dir=packages/react-reconciler/src \
  --old=ReactFiberExpirationTime.js \
  --new=ReactFiberLane.js
```

The default is to merge changes from the new module to the old one. To
merge changes in the opposite direction, use `--reverse`.

```sh
yarn merge-fork \
  --reverse \
  --base-dir=packages/react-reconciler/src \
  ReactFiberWorkLoop
```

By default, the changes are compared to HEAD. You can use `--base-ref`
to compare to any rev. For example, while working on a PR, you might
make multiple commits to the new fork before you're ready to backport
them to the old one. In that case, you want to compare to the merge
base of your PR branch:

```sh
yarn merge-fork \
  --base-ref=$(git merge-base HEAD origin/master)
  --base-dir=packages/react-reconciler/src \
  ReactFiberWorkLoop
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/devsumanmdn/react/commits/26fc16484e0586b65c7f549934354ef08f8d403e"},{"sha":"cbab25bb5159e82f0d74b0d2ad84d7ad7dd3613a","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"Exclude forwardRef and memo from stack frames (#18559)

[{"sha":"e6a7c7cc18c3aaad1ae0872cb0a959f5c923d2bd","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Remove `OP_REQUIRES` call from helper function.

Since `OP_REQUIRES` macro expands to a `return;` (among other), calling it in a helper function only ends the helper function's execution earlier, but the kernel will still run from start to end. Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

[{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

This should allow us to remove the logic in the event system that
tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

Change-Id: I40d8cb1ce462573c3d9ec0768c8d655841d1cf2b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/43c1ea6eed787254c814f2b2eb00bebf8d5b19df"},{"sha":"34eebc5712693d86839ca4b2800270bc91784b6d","author":{"name":"Markus Kunesch","email":"5f599223a28ad87148c6d9a71c50f73c37ac94c7@google.com"},"message":"xla: improvement to string representation of PyTreeDef

The string representation of PyTreeDef was different to how the underlying
containers are represented in python. This sometimes made it harder to read
error messages. This commit modifies the representation of tuples, lists,
dicts, and None so that it matches the pythonic representation.

The representation of custom nodes and NamedTuples is left unchanged since
their structure is not easily accessible in C++. However, to avoid confusion
they are now labelled "CustomNode" instead of "PyTreeDef". The latter is now
only used to wrap the whole representation. See below for examples.

Tests that relied on a specific string representation of PyTreeDef in error
messages are modified to be agnostic to the representation. Instead, this
commit adds a separate test of the string representation in tree_util_test.

Examples:

```
OLD: PyTreeDef(dict[['a', 'b']], [*,*])
NEW: PyTreeDef({'a': *, 'b': *})

OLD: PyTreeDef(tuple, [PyTreeDef(tuple, [*,*]),PyTreeDef(list, [*,PyTreeDef(tuple, [*,PyTreeDef(None, []),*])])])
NEW: PyTreeDef(((*, *), [*, (*, None, *)]))

OLD: PyTreeDef(list, [PyTreeDef(<class '__main__.AnObject'>[[4, 'foo']], [*,PyTreeDef(None, [])])])
NEW: PyTreeDef([CustomNode(<class '__main__.AnObject'>[[4, 'foo']], [*, None])])
```

Previously if there was a thread-local context set we would include it in preference to the global context. However since the "extra context" is an opaque object with no particular semantics as far as the C++ code is concerned, it makes more sense to include both local and global as part of the cache key. Just because the thread-local values are equal it doesn't mean that they completely override the global values.

The string representation of PyTreeDef was different to how the underlying
containers are represented in python. This sometimes made it harder to read
error messages. This commit modifies the representation of tuples, lists,
dicts, and None so that it matches the pythonic representation.

The representation of custom nodes and NamedTuples is left unchanged since
their structure is not easily accessible in C++. However, to avoid confusion
they are now labelled "CustomNode" instead of "PyTreeDef". The latter is now
only used to wrap the whole representation. See below for examples.

Tests that relied on a specific string representation of PyTreeDef in error
messages are modified to be agnostic to the representation. Instead, this
commit adds a separate test of the string representation in tree_util_test.

Examples:

```
OLD: PyTreeDef(dict[['a', 'b']], [*,*])
NEW: PyTreeDef({'a': *, 'b': *})

OLD: PyTreeDef(tuple, [PyTreeDef(tuple, [*,*]),PyTreeDef(list, [*,PyTreeDef(tuple, [*,PyTreeDef(None, []),*])])])
NEW: PyTreeDef(((*, *), [*, (*, None, *)]))

OLD: PyTreeDef(list, [PyTreeDef(<class '__main__.AnObject'>[[4, 'foo']], [*,PyTreeDef(None, [])])])
NEW: PyTreeDef([CustomNode(<class '__main__.AnObject'>[[4, 'foo']], [*, None])])
```

Previously if there was a thread-local context set we would include it in preference to the global context. However since the "extra context" is an opaque object with no particular semantics as far as the C++ code is concerned, it makes more sense to include both local and global as part of the cache key. Just because the thread-local values are equal it doesn't mean that they completely override the global values.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/awmirantis/moby/commits/452f82d5fc532e1bb4d005666148aa6bc28b97e6"},{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")
Signed-off-by: Michal Rostecki <mrostecki@opensuse.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/awmirantis/moby/commits/1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871"},{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

This should allow us to remove the logic in the event system that
tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

being unwrapped. This makes the QDQ inserting more flexible because all the
min/max operands of the tf.FakeQuant* ops have been folded already.

fake_quant_utils.

[{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

This should allow us to remove the logic in the event system that
tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]
